Author::::SybilSanderson
DateTime::::2016-03-05T16:40:08Z
Yes, I make it lot. What you describe has never happend to me. I use plain flour, not strong bread flour. Ratio flour to water is 2:1 ( four the dough), but you need a lot of flour to mold it (the flour on your work surface and hand). I also let it rest for up to 18 hours, no less than 12. You end up with an unbelievable stringy mess and it will spread quite a bit on the worksurface. Hence it is good if it is heavily floured. Just try to somehow fold it and let it rest again.And it is also important that the vessel, it is cooked in, is blazing hot, including the lid, before you dump the bread in. I use a Le Creuset for that. I never bother with the lid off at the final stage, if the vessel is hot enough you will get a strong dark crust even with the lid on.Have a look at the original video and you get the idea No-Knead Bread



Author::::mikedow
DateTime::::2016-03-05T16:23:25Z
Any fats added to a dough is called enrichment, and extends the shelf life a little longer. That's why standard French and Italian loaves are rock hard the next morning, an they create recipes to use up crusts and crumbs.



